Jim Albert

Linear Regression Problem

Fitting simple linear regression model for the cars dataset.

\[ y_i \sim N(a + b x_i, \sigma) \] (Priors will be described below.)

Gibbs / Metropolis Sampling

I am assuming that you have already installed the JAGS software on your computer. Load the rjags package which provides an interface to JAGS.

library(rjags)

Write a script that describes the Bayesian model. Note that JAGS parameterizes the normal distribution in terms of the precision which is the reciprocal of the variance. Also note the weakly informative priors assigned to the precision and the regression coefficients.

model_string <- "model{
  # Likelihood
  for(i in 1:n){
    Y[i]   ~ dnorm(mu[i], inv.var)
    mu[i] <- beta[1]  + beta[2] * x[i]
  }
  # Prior for beta
  for(j in 1:2){
    beta[j] ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
  }
  # Prior for the inverse variance
  inv.var   ~ dgamma(0.01, 0.01)
  sigma     <- 1/sqrt(inv.var)
}"

The jags.model function sets up the model. The arguments are the model script and the data which is a list with components Y, n, and x.

model <- jags.model(textConnection(model_string), 
               data = list(Y=cars$dist,
                           n=length(cars$dist),
                           x=cars$speed))

## Initializing model

First have a burn-in period of 10,000 iterations and then collect the next 10,000 iterations. Compute posterior summaries of all parameters.

update(model, 10000, progress.bar="none")
samp <- coda.samples(model, 
        variable.names=c("beta","sigma"), 
        n.iter=10000, progress.bar="none")
summary(samp)
